diagnoses.name: Stevens-Johnson Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A rare, serious disorder of the skin and mucous membranes. Often a reaction to a medication or an infection.

diagnoses.name: Toxic Epidermal Necrolysis
diagnoses.description: A severe skin condition that involves necrosis and detachment of the epidermis. It's often triggered by medications or an infection.

diagnoses.name: Behçet's Disease
diagnoses.description: A rare disorder causing blood vessel inflammation throughout your body, leading to numerous symptoms including mouth and genital sores.

diagnoses.name: Kawasaki Disease
diagnoses.description: A condition that causes inflammation in the walls of some blood vessels in the body. It’s most common in children.

diagnoses.name: Infectious Mononucleosis
diagnoses.description: Often called mono, it's an infection usually caused by the Epstein-Barr virus (EBV) that causes fever, sore throat, swollen lymph glands, and fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Herpes Simplex Virus
diagnoses.description: A viral infection that can cause sores or blisters around the mouth (oral herpes) or genitals (genital herpes).

diagnoses.name: Drug Reaction with Eosinophilia and Systemic Symptoms (DRESS) Syndrome
diagnoses.description: A drug reaction that causes a severe skin rash, fever, lymphadenopathy, hematological abnormalities, and often affects internal organs.

diagnoses.name: Streptococcal Pharyngitis
diagnoses.description: A bacterial infection that can cause a sore, scratchy throat. It is sometimes associated with scarlet fever which can present with a rash.

diagnoses.name: Urinary Tract Infection
diagnoses.description: An infection in any part of the urinary system, kidneys, bladder, or urethra. Pyuria is a common finding.

diagnoses.name: Henoch-Schönlein Purpura
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the blood vessels that can cause rash, abdominal pain, and joint inflammation. It often follows an infection.

diagnoses.name: Graves' Disease
diagnoses.reasoning: Hyperthyroidism and dysgeusia are common symptoms, and in some cases, it could lead to goiter which might affect the glucose metabolism indirectly contributing to hypoglycemia.

diagnoses.name: Essential Thrombocythemia
diagnoses.reasoning: Mainly characterized by thrombocytosis but can also indirectly influence glucose metabolism, possibly leading to hypoglycemia. Symptoms might also be confused with or contribute to dysgeusia.

diagnoses.name: Ehlers-Danlos Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: Directly noted for hypermobility but can also have an indirect effect or associations with dysgeusia and hypoglycemia through gastrointestinal symptoms and possible autoimmune overlap with thyroid disorders.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.reasoning: Though primarily characterized by an increased number of erythrocytes, it can lead to thrombocytosis. Also, metabolic changes including altered glucose metabolism can be a feature.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.reasoning: While not directly causing hypermobility or hyperthyroidism, it can cause thrombocytosis. Dysgeusia and hypoglycemia can also present as symptoms of severe cases.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.reasoning: Primarily associated with dysglycemia, which can lead to both hypoglycemia and indirectly influence thrombocytosis. Dysgeusia is a known but less common symptom.

diagnoses.name: Primary Hyperparathyroidism
diagnoses.reasoning: Can cause hypercalcemia which may induce hyperthyroid-like symptoms, contribute to thrombocytosis, and impact blood glucose levels.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Endocrine Neoplasia Type 1 (MEN1)
diagnoses.reasoning: A condition that could precipitate hyperthyroidism, affect calcium and glucose metabolism, potentially leading to hypoglycemia, and possibly thrombocytosis through varying mechanisms depending on the specific endocrine glands involved.

diagnoses.name: Paraneoplastic Syndromes
diagnoses.reasoning: Certain cancers can cause a distant effect on blood cells leading to thrombocytosis and also impact metabolic processes including that of thyroid and glucose, potentially resulting in dysgeusia.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.reasoning: An autoimmune condition that can manifest with a wide range of symptoms including dysgeusia and hypoglycemia. There's potential for thrombocytosis and the autoimmune nature can also involve the thyroid.

diagnoses: Polycystic ovary syndrome (as a differential for endometriosis)
Chronic sinusitis (as a potential cause of congestion)
Postnasal Drip Syndrome (Upper Airway Cough Syndrome)

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that often features symptoms including dry eyes and post-nasal drip due to its effect on moisture-producing glands.

diagnoses.name: Sarcoidosis
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory disease that can cause fibrosis in various organs including the lungs, skin, and eyes, potentially leading to symptoms like dry eyes and post-nasal drip.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus (SLE)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that can cause widespread inflammation and tissue damage in the affected organs, including the skin, joints, and kidneys, potentially contributing to hyperthermia and osteopenia.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that can cause dry eyes and osteopenia due to inflammation of the joints and potential effects on the eyes and bones.

diagnoses.name: Idiopathic Pulmonary Fibrosis
diagnoses.description: A condition characterized by progressive scarring (fibrosis) of the lung tissue, leading to worsening dyspnea (difficulty breathing), though less commonly associated with the mentioned symptoms.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: HIV can lead to a wide range of secondary infections and conditions due to immunosuppression, potentially manifesting in symptoms like fibrosis, dry eyes, and post-nasal drip.

diagnoses.name: Primary Biliary Cholangitis
diagnoses.description: A chronic disease that slowly destroys the bile ducts in the liver, potentially leading to fibrosis. Associated sicca symptoms (such as dry eyes) may resemble those of Sjögren's syndrome.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Hepatitis
diagnoses.description: Infections of the liver that are long-term can lead to fibrosis and cirrhosis as the liver attempts to heal itself, occasionally leading to secondary symptoms discussed.

diagnoses.name: Graft-versus-Host Disease (GvHD)
diagnoses.description: A condition that occurs when donor bone marrow or stem cells attack the recipient, potentially causing fibrosis, dry eyes, and other systemic symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Mixed Connective Tissue Disease (MCTD)
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder that may manifest symptoms similar to those of SLE, scleroderma, and polymyositis, including potential osteopenia and dry eyes.

diagnoses: Hashimoto's Thyroiditis leading to transient Hyperthyroidism

diagnoses.name: Chronic Myeloproliferative Disorders
diagnoses.description: A group of conditions that cause blood cells -- platelets, white blood cells, and red blood cells -- to grow abnormally in the bone marrow.

diagnoses.name: Essential Thrombocythemia
diagnoses.description: A rare chronic blood disorder characterized by the overproduction of platelets by megakaryocytes in the bone marrow without an identifiable cause, leading to thrombocytosis.

diagnoses.name: Polycythemia Vera
diagnoses.description: A blood cancer that causes the bone marrow to make too many red blood cells; it can also cause an increase in white blood cells and platelets.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Lymphocytic Leukemia
diagnoses.description: A type of cancer in which the bone marrow makes too many lymphocytes (a type of white blood cell). It can lead to enlargement of the lymph nodes (lymphadenitis) and affect liver function.

diagnoses.name: Hodgkin's Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A type of lymphoma characterized by the presence of Reed-Sternberg cells. Symptoms may include swelling of the lymph nodes (lymphadenitis), fever, and fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune Hepatitis
diagnoses.description: A chronic disease in which your body's immune system attacks your liver, possibly causing high liver enzymes, among other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.description: A long-term condition characterized by a gradual loss of kidney function over time. It can lead to hypertension and affect other organs.

diagnoses.name: Hemochromatosis
diagnoses.description: An inherited disorder causing the body to absorb too much iron from the diet. The excess iron is stored in various organs, especially the liver, heart, and pancreas, potentially leading to abnormal liver enzymes and other symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Systemic Lupus Erythematosus
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease that can cause inflammation and damage to various body systems, including the joints, skin, kidneys, blood cells, brain, heart, and lungs.

diagnoses.name: Non-Hodgkin's Lymphoma
diagnoses.description: A type of lymphoma characterized by the absence of Reed-Sternberg cells. It can present with lymphadenitis, abnormal liver enzymes, and other systemic symptoms.

diagnoses: Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) with comorbid conditions

diagnoses.name: Polycystic Ovary Syndrome (PCOS)
diagnoses.reasoning: PCOS can lead to symptoms such as infertility, anxiety due to hormonal imbalance, and insulin resistance which might indirectly go along with skin conditions like acne or folliculitis.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.reasoning: Hypothyroidism can contribute to symptoms like infertility, anxiety, and hypersomnolence due to the lowered production of thyroid hormones.

diagnoses.name: Sleep Apnea
diagnoses.reasoning: Sleep apnea can cause hypersomnolence and anxiety due to poor sleep quality and might indirectly affect fertility.

diagnoses.name: Depression
diagnoses.reasoning: Depression can manifest with anxiety, hypersomnolence, and sometimes impact physical conditions, potentially exacerbating conditions like folliculitis through neglect of skincare routines.

diagnoses.name: Iron Overload Disorders (Hemochromatosis)
diagnoses.reasoning: Hemochromatosis could explain hyperferritinemia and has been associated with fatigue, which might overlap with hypersomnolence. It can indirectly influence fertility.

diagnoses.name: Anxiety Disorders
diagnoses.reasoning: Anxiety itself could be primary, influencing sleep patterns (hypersomnolence) and potentially exacerbating skin conditions like folliculitis due to stress-related behaviors.

diagnoses.name: Cushing's Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: Cushing's syndrome can lead to a variety of symptoms including anxiety, hypersomnolence, and possibly influence fertility due to hormonal imbalances.

diagnoses.name: Primary Immunodeficiency Diseases
diagnoses.reasoning: Certain immunodeficiencies can manifest as recurrent skin infections (folliculitis) and could indirectly affect overall health leading to symptoms like hypersomnolence and fertility issues.

diagnoses.name: Stress-Related Disorders
diagnoses.reasoning: Chronic stress can manifest physically and psychologically, causing or exacerbating symptoms such as anxiety, hypersomnolence, and folliculitis, indirectly affecting fertility.

diagnoses.name: Metabolic Syndrome
diagnoses.reasoning: Metabolic syndrome could indirectly contribute to issues like infertility and anxiety through its associated conditions like obesity and insulin resistance, which can also impact skin health.

diagnoses.name: Vitamin A Deficiency
diagnoses.description: Vitamin A deficiency can manifest as night blindness, dry eyes, susceptibility to infections, and skin issues. Prolonged deficiency may lead go xerophthalmia and keratomalacia, affecting the eyes, and contribute to periodontal disease due to impaired immune response. Malabsorption issues can lead to this deficiency.

diagnoses.name: Celiac Disease
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where ingestion of gluten leads to damage in the small intestine, causing malabsorption of nutrients which can lead to a wide range of symptoms including irritability, and dental problems such as periodontal disease.

diagnoses.name: Crohn's Disease
diagnoses.description: An inflammatory bowel disease (IBD) that can cause malabsorption, leading to various nutritional deficiencies. Patients may experience a wide range of symptoms, including chronic bronchitis, irritability, and mouth ulcers which are indicative of periodontal issues.

diagnoses.name: Cystic Fibrosis
diagnoses.description: A genetic disorder that affects the lungs and digestive system, leading to chronic lung infections (like bronchitis) and malabsorption issues. It can also lead to vitamin A deficiency, potentially causing eye irritation.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Obstructive Pulmonary Disease (COPD)
diagnoses.description: A group of lung diseases that block airflow and make it difficult to breathe, often leading to chronic bronchitis. Smoking is a common cause, which can also aggravate periodontal disease.

diagnoses.name: Sjögren's Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An immune system disorder characterized by dry eyes and dry mouth. The condition can lead to dental and periodontal problems due to decreased saliva production, and the systemic inflammatory response can affect the digestive system, potentially leading to malabsorption.

diagnoses.name: HIV/AIDS
diagnoses.description: HIV damages the immune system and severely impacts the body’s ability to fight off infections. This can lead to periodontal disease, malabsorption due to gastrointestinal tract infections, irritability from the overall effect on health, and bronchitis or other opportunistic infections.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.description: Poorly controlled diabetes can lead to a weakened immune system, making individuals more susceptible to infections such as periodontal disease and bronchitis. Diabetes can also cause complications that lead to eye irritation.

diagnoses.name: Rheumatoid Arthritis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease that causes chronic inflammation of the joints and can involve other parts of the body. It can be associated with periodontal disease, eye irritation due to secondary Sjögren's syndrome, and may contribute to irritability and malabsorption if the gastrointestinal tract is affected.

diagnoses.name: Iron Deficiency Anemia
diagnoses.description: Iron deficiency can lead to anemia, causing irritability and reduced immune function, which may increase susceptibility to infections like periodontal disease. Malabsorption syndromes can contribute to iron deficiency.

diagnoses: Connective tissue diseases (e.g., Rheumatoid Arthritis, Lupus)
Atopic dermatitis (which can lead to Otitis externa due to skin conditions)
Allergic rhinitis (can be related to cough and sometimes hyperactivity due to discomfort)
Asthma (cough as a symptom, possibly exacerbated by environmental allergens, can coexist with immunodeficiencies)
Attention deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD) (if focusing strictly on hyperactivity and interpreting other symptoms as possibly separate or indirectly related conditions)
Vitamin Deficiencies – Certain vitamin deficiencies (like B12 or folate) could indirectly correlate with these symptoms through neuropathy, anemia, and metabolic disarray.
Neurodegenerative Disorders – Conditions like Alzheimer’s or Parkinson’s disease can cause dysosmia and seizures, alongside metabolic disturbances.
Iron Deficiency Anemia – This condition directly leads to hypoferritinemia and can be associated with dysosmia and, in severe cases, neurological symptoms like seizures.
Hypothyroidism – Thyroid disorders could manifest broadly, affecting metabolic rate (dyslipidemia), energy levels (potentially influencing seizure thresholds), and even olfactory function.

Celiac Disease – This autoimmune disorder can lead to a wide array of deficiencies (including iron), contributing to hypoferritinemia, seizures (due to neurological involvement), and sometimes dyslipidemia.
Epilepsy – Primary seizure disorders might also indirectly affect olfactory functions, and ongoing stress from seizures can influence lipid metabolism and iron stores.
Multiple Sclerosis (MS) – MS can present with seizures and olfactory dysfunction (dysosmia). Chronic inflammation associated with MS can influence lipid metabolism and iron levels.
Chronic Kidney Disease (CKD) – CKD can lead to dyslipidemia and hypoferritinemia due to reduced kidney function. It can also be associated indirectly with seizures and neurological issues.

Liver Disease – Hepatic dysfunction can manifest as dyslipidemia and affect iron metabolism (hypoferritinemia). Liver disease can also be linked to neurological dysfunction, potentially contributing to seizures and olfactory issues.

Autoimmune Disorders – Systemic lupus erythematosus (SLE) and other autoimmune conditions can impact multiple bodily systems, potentially causing dyslipidemia, hypoferritinemia, neurologic symptoms (including seizures), and sensory dysfunctions like dysosmia.

diagnoses.name: Age-related Hearing Loss (Presbycusis)
diagnoses.rationale: Common in aging, which may also explain the presence of atherosclerosis due to shared risk factors.

diagnoses.name: Atherosclerotic Cardiovascular Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Directly corresponds to the symptom of atherosclerosis; could contribute indirectly to other symptoms through decreased organ perfusion.

diagnoses.name: Diabetes Mellitus
diagnoses.rationale: Can cause mood lability through fluctuations in blood glucose. Also, diabetes can lead to atherosclerosis, contribute to the risk of urinary tract infections, and potentially affect hearing.

diagnoses.name: Major Depression Disorder
diagnoses.rationale: Mood lability is a key symptom, and depression could be indirectly linked to other symptoms like dyspepsia due to changes in lifestyle or neglect of health.

diagnoses.name: Chronic Kidney Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Can lead to a variety of metabolic imbalances affecting mood, contribute to atherosclerosis development, and increase susceptibility to urinary tract infections.

diagnoses.name: Hypertension
diagnoses.rationale: Closely associated with atherosclerosis and could indirectly be related to several of the other symptoms through vascular damage.

diagnoses.name: Functional Dyspepsia
diagnoses.rationale: Directly corresponds to the symptom of dyspepsia; it's a common gastroenterological condition that might not be directly related to the other symptoms but is significant enough to be considered.

diagnoses.name: Ménière's Disease
diagnoses.rationale: Though primarily known for causing vertigo, it can also result in hearing loss and might contribute to mood lability due to the chronic nature of the disease.

diagnoses.name: Hypothyroidism
diagnoses.rationale: Can cause mood lability, contribute to the risk of atherosclerosis through altered lipid metabolism, and potential to indirectly affect hearing.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms including severe headaches, visual disturbances, vertigo, and sensitivity to sounds (phonophobia). Aphasia and auditory symptoms can occasionally be associated with complex migraines.

diagnoses.name: Ménière's disease
diagnoses.description: A disorder of the inner ear that causes episodes of feeling like you're spinning (vertigo), ringing in the ear (tinnitus), hearing loss, and a fullness in the ear. It can lead to permanent hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Vestibular migraine
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that predominantly affects balance and can cause vertigo, dizziness, and balance problems, sometimes accompanied by headaches, phonophobia, and auditory symptoms.

diagnoses.name: Acoustic neuroma
diagnoses.description: A benign tumor on the cranial nerve that connects the inner ear with the brain. Symptoms can include hearing loss, vertigo, and tinnitus. Headaches and other symptoms may occur as the tumor grows.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition that occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, leading to symptoms such as aphasia, vertigo, and, in some cases, headache and hearing issues.

diagnoses.name: Multiple sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic illness of the central nervous system. Symptoms can vary widely but may include fatigue, dizziness (vertigo), speech disturbances (including aphasia), and episodes of pain and hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Temporal arteritis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of blood vessels, often in the head, causing headache, jaw pain, vision problems, and sometimes symptoms like hearing loss.

diagnoses.name: Otitis media
diagnoses.description: An infection of the middle ear that can present with hearing loss, balance disturbances (including vertigo), and occasionally headache.

diagnoses.name: Brain tumor
diagnoses.description: Any tumor located in the brain can lead to a variety of neurological symptoms depending on its location and size, including headaches, seizures, cognitive or speech disturbances (such as aphasia), hearing loss, and sometimes vertigo.

diagnoses.name: Autoimmune inner ear disease
diagnoses.description: A rare condition where the immune system attacks the inner ear, leading to progressive hearing loss and occasionally balance issues such as vertigo. Additional symptoms can include tinnitus and a feeling of fullness in the ear.

diagnoses: Secondary headache associated with intracranial disorder
Secondary headache associated with substance use or withdrawal

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A condition where poor blood flow to the brain results in cell death, causing symptoms such as aphasia, headache, and weakness.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: An abnormal growth of cells within the brain that can cause pressure effects and symptoms like headache, weakness, and aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack (TIA)
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, it presents with temporary stroke-like symptoms such as aphasia, weakness, and can include headache.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: A type of migraine that can involve temporary visual or sensory disturbances followed by a headache, and sometimes includes weakness or speech difficulties.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disease affecting the brain and spinal cord, leading to symptoms like weakness, changes in speech (including aphasia), and headaches.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the brain, caused by an infection or autoimmune response. Symptoms can include headache, weakness, aphasia, among others.

diagnoses.name: Brain Abscess
diagnoses.description: A collection of pus caused by an infection within the brain tissue, leading to symptoms such as headaches, weakness, and potentially aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Epilepsy (Postictal State)
diagnoses.description: After a seizure, individuals may experience a range of symptoms including headache, confusion, weakness, and difficulties with speech.

diagnoses.name: Hemorrhagic Stroke
diagnoses.description: Occurs when a blood vessel in the brain bursts, causing symptoms similar to an ischemic stroke: headache, weakness, and possibly aphasia.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An infection of the protective membranes covering the brain and spinal cord. Symptoms can include severe headache, weakness, and in later stages, problems with speech.

diagnoses.name: Migraine
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition characterized by intense headaches often accompanied by nausea, vomiting, and sensitivity to light and sound.

diagnoses.name: Cluster Headache
diagnoses.description: Severe, recurring headaches on one side of the head, typically around the eye, accompanied by symptoms such as redness of the eye, tearing, and nasal congestion.

diagnoses.name: Tension Headache
diagnoses.description: A common type of headache characterized by pressure or tightness around the forehead or back of the head and neck.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A medical condition that occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted or reduced, preventing brain tissue from receiving oxygen and nutrients.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic, typically progressive disease involving damage to the sheaths of nerve cells in the brain and spinal cord, whose symptoms may include numbness, impairment of speech and of muscular coordination, blurred vision, and severe fatigue.

diagnoses.name: Meningitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the protective membranes covering the brain and spinal cord, known collectively as the meninges. This condition may develop in response to a number of causes, including infections, drugs, or other diseases.

diagnoses.name: Optic Neuritis
diagnoses.description: Inflammation of the optic nerve that can cause a sudden reduction of vision in the affected eye, pain with eye movement, and on occasion, symptoms including flashing lights.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: A mass or growth of abnormal cells in the brain. Symptoms depend on the size, type, and location of the tumor but may include headaches, seizures, and cognitive or personality changes.

diagnoses.name: Subarachnoid Hemorrhage
diagnoses.description: Bleeding in the space between the brain and the tissue covering the brain, often signalled by a sudden, severe headache. It's a medical emergency.

diagnoses.name: Encephalitis
diagnoses.description: An inflammation of the brain, often caused by a viral infection. Symptoms can be mild, like a headache, or severe, like a fever, confusion, or seizures.

diagnoses.name: Migraine with Aura
diagnoses.description: Migraines with aura are characterized by temporary visual, sensory, language, or motor disturbances preceding or accompanying the headache. Symptoms like scintillation, numbness, and phonophobia are common in this condition.

diagnoses.name: Multiple Sclerosis
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disease affecting the central nervous system, marked by symptoms such as numbness, weakness, lack of coordination, and speech disturbances including dysphagia.

diagnoses.name: Transient Ischemic Attack
diagnoses.description: Often called a mini-stroke, a TIA presents with brief episodes of neurological dysfunction, including numbness, paralysis, and speech impairment, without causing permanent brain damage.

diagnoses.name: Stroke
diagnoses.description: A stroke occurs when the blood supply to part of the brain is interrupted, leading to symptoms like numbness, paralysis on one side of the body, and difficulty speaking or swallowing.

diagnoses.name: Guillain-Barre Syndrome
diagnoses.description: An autoimmune disorder where the body's immune system attacks the nerves, leading to muscle weakness, tingling in the extremities, and in severe cases, paralysis.

diagnoses.name: Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis (ALS)
diagnoses.description: Also known as Lou Gehrig’s disease, ALS affects the nerve cells responsible for controlling voluntary muscle movement. Symptoms include difficulty speaking, swallowing, and progressive paralysis.

diagnoses.name: Peripheral Neuropathy
diagnoses.description: Damage to the peripheral nerves causing weakness, numbness, and pain, usually in the hands and feet. It can result from traumatic injuries, infections, metabolic problems, and exposure to toxins.

diagnoses.name: Myasthenia Gravis
diagnoses.description: A chronic autoimmune disorder characterized by weakness and rapid fatigue of any of the muscles under voluntary control. Common symptoms include a drooping eyelid, blurred or double vision, slurred speech, and difficulty swallowing.

diagnoses.name: Migraine without Aura
diagnoses.description: A neurological condition that can cause multiple symptoms. It’s frequently characterized by intense, debilitating headaches. Symptoms may include nausea, phonophobia, and light sensitivity, but no aura is present.

diagnoses.name: Brain Tumor
diagnoses.description: Abnormal growths of cells in the brain that can be cancerous or noncancerous. Depending on their location, they can cause a wide range of neurological symptoms, including numbness, difficulty with speech, and partial loss of vision.
